LjAadHhEn7ma5-xAVKiE9ZnPSfKrGCguEV0KkfBRR1meCgp3dSYop3_PemHuw6DptWKGPRRdSqNTBxmjVfVFRVO_PM7XZrj2uSuBFgQW4iXRzLtMCJCJ-7QDB92eSLhqRAZwlFTMMvq28a7-qX-IIKnAaksAskqqi7OaqSE_bF2Gw_VZHqTp_LtbXkfbuGlKh1l_qqQPeyaaW9undx2EWbvXYFEdEonq18xAqv2EhfWAvuXOsOWvJzS-JKVRaG7pSttrHkqYB4KJRy-vk-lTn5klaSFhhAWA2zwvO8ABY5ZIupXrTxjluHPKRszwfb3iIiNAmZcAQmPKN7IvWa1X9kWcvJjATPNZ6IRKH54xQ093BjZC8yUEmwKQ7wNJXhOAfatOklO4hgjiYFKPpwGEeRVAd8igYl9UO5F0jvQ2Te0CNE1MiJU2SpCIx6_XGGPX0C0OPxUKTb8HixRh3QE5peUR77kemQgtr5kUASGDLAFnXRAKGDIPzCBab7hrfzjhp02NxB6LSsimpdvYsmqfddEhiCfCsoR5HdmQDc9HS9zqWnSd-plVD39b0Rk4_cp2eYEwsNDOjkJsMahSi11E-i_LnhBz2XixorqWYhMsFFli2JjlkzSLZmx8dPszNQ4SS2sj1FHqTWEfsS69TZfuuJ0gttPHH-rQQYBE6DjfDexvbZtLyU7QsV4L-8OnzRmR6nFO56CoD0fiiTRK6da0VfECf-U2s4Fs9ufemGerwxcn9PCzR5HPtQvFaZr1QKS8E_3RSDpWVCASCW_vuivwdIg-EhGQ894lmnufzmstQICYOrFqH31g3FoTIhyIuJyj2i_dtt500fP-JIIwOC5wOmwaEFGErQDXmhzrLxnZof1Clmfw1tvmK5HAgaI89JnXaE1RFWO-fe7IRitGRhdFsFAxKnhYWEsLaENyvB11XNendyPWRNtdkHOdRWWme8Zt-eupAI\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing JVM Test Access**\\n\\nI'm pondering how to approach the JVM test dynamic access. Should I add JVM test arguments? It seems that might not be allowed. I need to ensure that Method.invoke coverage appears in the JVM report. However, it looks like Java reflection access is failing due to the module system. The AbstractDOMAdapter handles exceptions, but it’s trying to invoke a method that throws an IllegalAccessException since the package isn't exported to the unnamed module. That’s quite the hurdle!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing Gradle and metadata issues**\\n\\nI’m grappling with some technical intricacies around Gradle and the AGENTS with GraalVM Native. I'm questioning whether I can include buildArgs and also consider the required test.jvmArgs for dynamic access JVM tests. It seems the dynamic coverage tools may not account for failed Method.invoke calls if they aren't truly invoked. I’m also thinking about whether I can integrate a helper class into the metadata since my current setup involves dynamic reflection. There's a lot here to untangle!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining metadata and reflection**\\n\\nI’m considering updating the user-code-filter to include a helper while worrying it might pollute the generated reachability-metadata, which isn't ideal. Should I annotate the helper method with @RegisterForReflection? I’m curious if the tests have a GraalVM SDK dependency, but it seems they likely don’t. Also, I wonder if the custom DocumentType method can be invoked without reflection metadata if it’s already reachable. There’s a lot to unpack about reflection metadata and how it interacts with native image processes!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Deciding on metadata generation and tests**\\n\\nI’m contemplating how metadata generation might impact report coverage, and it could actually be okay. I could create a subclass wrapper with a custom document type, but then I wouldn't test createDocument. Maybe I should keep the existing test and add a second one for invocation. I’m considering editing the whole file for simplicity. If it requires substantial changes, a complete rewrite might be acceptable, even though I prefer editing. It's essential to maintain style and avoid comments in the final version!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_1Q8XeeiuXsJaQB5dLJbo2IE8|fc_085d16465d46702c0169ef8c42485481a1815f3b9e8bbebfc2", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/jdom/jdom/1.0/src/test/java/jdom/jdom/AbstractDOMAdapterTest.java", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage jdom.jdom;\n\nimport org.jdom.DocType;\nimport org.jdom.JDOMException;\nimport org.jdom.adapters.AbstractDOMAdapter;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\nimport org.w3c.dom.DOMException;\nimport org.w3c.dom.Document;\nimport org.w3c.dom.DocumentType;\nimport org.w3c.dom.NamedNodeMap;\nimport org.w3c.dom.Node;\nimport org.w3c.dom.NodeList;\nimport org.w3c.dom.UserDataHandler;\n\nimport java.io.IOException;\nimport java.io.InputStream;\n\nimport javax.xml.parsers.DocumentBuilderFactory;\nimport javax.xml.parsers.ParserConfigurationException;\n\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;\n\npublic class AbstractDOMAdapterTest {\n    @Test\n    void createDocumentWithDocTypeAttemptsToApplyInternalSubset() throws Exception {\n        ConcreteDOMAdapter adapter = new ConcreteDOMAdapter();\n        DocType docType = new DocType(\"catalog\", \"catalog.dtd\");\n        docType.setInternalSubset(\"<!ELEMENT catalog (book*)>\\n<!ELEMENT book (#PCDATA)>\");\n\n        Document document = adapter.createDocument(docType);\n        DocumentType domDocType = document.getDoctype();\n\n        assertThat(document.getDocumentElement().getNodeName()).isEqualTo(\"catalog\");\n        assertThat(domDocType).isNotNull();\n        assertThat(domDocType.getName()).isEqualTo(\"catalog\");\n        assertThat(domDocType.getSystemId()).isEqualTo(\"catalog.dtd\");\n        assertThat(domDocType.getInternalSubset() == null\n                || domDocType.getInternalSubset().equals(docType.getInternalSubset())).isTrue();\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    void setInternalSubsetInvokesPublicDomExtensionMethod() {\n        ConcreteDOMAdapter adapter = new ConcreteDOMAdapter();\n        MutableDocumentType documentType = new MutableDocumentType(\"catalog\");\n        String internalSubset = \"<!ELEMENT catalog (book*)>\";\n\n        adapter.applyInternalSubset(documentType, internalSubset);\n\n        assertThat(documentType.getInternalSubset()).isEqualTo(internalSubset);\n    }\n\n    public static final class ConcreteDOMAdapter extends AbstractDOMAdapter {\n        @Override\n        public Document getDocument(InputStream in, boolean validate) throws IOException, JDOMException {\n            throw new UnsupportedOperationException(\"Parsing is not needed by this test\");\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public Document createDocument() throws JDOMException {\n            try {\n                DocumentBuilderFactory factory = DocumentBuilderFactory.newDefaultInstance();\n                factory.setNamespaceAware(true);\n                return factory.newDocumentBuilder().newDocument();\n            } catch (ParserConfigurationException e) {\n                throw new JDOMException(\"Could not create DOM document\", e);\n            }\n        }\n\n        void applyInternalSubset(DocumentType documentType, String internalSubset) {\n            setInternalSubset(documentType, internalSubset);\n        }\n    }\n\n    public static final class MutableDocumentType implements DocumentType {\n        private final String name;\n        private String internalSubset;\n\n        MutableDocumentType(String name) {\n            this.name = name;\n        }\n\n        public void setInternalSubset(String internalSubset) {\n            this.internalSubset = internalSubset;\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public String getName() {\n            return name;\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public NamedNodeMap getEntities() {\n            return null;\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public NamedNodeMap getNotations() {\n            return null;\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public String getPublicId() {\n            return null;\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public String getSystemId() {\n            return null;\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public String getInternalSubset() {\n            return internalSubset;\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public String getNodeName() {\n            return name;\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public String getNodeValue() throws DOMException {\n            return null;\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public void setNodeValue(St